 encouraging limits on women's freedom.Sikata Banerjee notes that the nationalism defined by masculine Hinduism draws on a more general narrative of nation found in many cultures. If the outcomes of this narrative are to be resisted, the logic of masculinity, armed manhood, and nation need to be examined in diverse contexts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aHinduism and statezIndia. 0aMasculinityxReligious aspectsxHinduism. 0aNationalism and feminismzIndiaxReligious aspects. 0aNationalismxReligious aspectsxHinduism. 4aAsian Studies : India and South Asian Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Gender Studies. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Hindu Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791483695423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791483695/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles